    "en": "<p><strong>Duvdu Terms and Conditions</strong></p><p><strong>Last Updated:</strong> <i>[01 May 2025]</i></p><p><strong>Introduction</strong></p><p>Welcome to <strong>Duvdu</strong>, a freelancing platform for creatives operating in Egypt. These Terms and Conditions (the <strong>“Terms”</strong> or <strong>“Agreement”</strong>) govern your access to and use of the Duvdu website and mobile applications (collectively, the <strong>“Platform”</strong>). This Agreement is a legal contract between you (<strong>“User”</strong>, <strong>“you”</strong>, or <strong>“your”</strong>) and Duvdu (referred to as <strong>“Duvdu”</strong>, <strong>“we”</strong>, <strong>“us”</strong>, or <strong>“the Platform”</strong>). By creating an account or using any part of the Platform, you acknowledge that you have read, understood, and agree to be bound by these Terms, as well as our Privacy Policy and any other guidelines or policies referenced herein. If you do not agree with any part of these Terms, you must not use the Platform.</p><p>Duvdu provides an online venue where Clients and Freelancers can connect and collaborate on creative projects. We facilitate matching and provide tools such as communication channels and an escrow payment system to enable Users to work together. <strong>Duvdu is not a party to any contract for services between the Client and the Freelancer; the agreement for the work is solely between those two parties</strong>. Our role is limited to providing the platform and intermediary services (including payment holding via escrow and dispute resolution support) to make such freelance engagements possible.</p><p>These Terms contain important information about your rights and obligations, as well as conditions, limitations, and exclusions that might apply to you. We have organized the document into clear sections, including specific provisions for <strong>Freelancers</strong> (service providers) and <strong>Clients</strong> (service buyers). Please read this Agreement carefully before using Duvdu. If you are using the Platform on behalf of a company or other legal entity, you represent that you have the authority to bind that entity to these Terms (in which case, references to “you” mean the entity). You should print or save a local copy of these Terms for your records.</p><p><strong>Definitions</strong></p><p>For the purpose of this Agreement, the following terms have these meanings:</p><ul><li><strong>Client</strong> – A User who posts a project or requests services on the Platform, or who engages a Freelancer to perform services. A Client is sometimes referred to as a “Service Buyer.”</li><li><strong>Freelancer</strong> – A User who offers and provides services through the Platform to Clients. A Freelancer is sometimes referred to as a “Service Provider.”</li><li><strong>Project</strong> – The collaboration or job agreed upon between a Client and a Freelancer via Duvdu. A Project may consist of a one-time task or a series of tasks, and it may be divided into milestones.</li><li><strong>Milestone</strong> – A defined deliverable or segment of a Project for which a portion of the payment is held in escrow and released upon completion of that segment. Milestones break a Project into smaller parts with corresponding payments.</li><li><strong>Escrow Account</strong> – A temporary holding account managed by Duvdu (or its payment agent) where the Client’s funds are held securely until the conditions for release are met. Funds in escrow are eventually released to the Freelancer upon completion and approval of the work, or refunded to the Client under certain conditionseces.org.eg.</li><li><strong>Commission</strong> (or <strong>Service Fee</strong>) – The fee that Duvdu charges for use of the Platform’s services, typically a percentage of the Project payment or a fixed amount, which serves as Duvdu’s remuneration for facilitating the transaction.</li><li><strong>Deliverables</strong> – The work products, files, or results that the Freelancer must deliver to the Client as per the Project’s requirements.</li><li><strong>Dispute</strong> – A formal disagreement raised on the Platform by a Client or Freelancer regarding a Project, usually concerning the quality, delivery, or payment for the work.</li><li><strong>User Content</strong> – Information that Users provide or post on the Platform, such as profile details, project descriptions, messages, files, ratings, or feedback.</li><li><strong>Agreement</strong> – Refers to these Terms and Conditions, i.e., the entire contract between you and Duvdu governing the use of the Platform.</li></ul><p>These definitions are provided for clarity. Additional terms may be defined elsewhere in the text of the Agreement. In this document, words in the singular include the plural and vice versa, and headings are for convenience only and do not affect interpretation.</p><p><strong>Account Registration and User Eligibility</strong></p><p>To access most features of Duvdu, you must register and maintain an active account. The following rules apply to account creation and maintenance:</p><ul><li><strong>Eligibility:</strong> You must <strong>be at least 18 years old</strong> (or the age of legal majority in your jurisdiction, if higher) to register for a Duvdu account and use our services. By creating an account, you represent and warrant that you are 18 or older and legally capable of forming binding contracts. If you are between 15 and 18 years old, you may use the Platform <strong>only with the involvement and consent of a parent or legal guardian</strong>, who must supervise your activities and will be held responsible for your account. Users under 15 years of age are not permitted to use Duvdu.</li><li><strong>Accurate Information:</strong> You agree to provide true, accurate, and complete information during the registration process (including your name, valid email address, and any other required details) and to update your information promptly if it changes. Misrepresenting your identity or skills is prohibited. Each User is responsible for the accuracy of the information associated with their account.</li><li><strong>Account Security:</strong> You are responsible for maintaining the confidentiality of your account login credentials. You must not share your password or allow others to access your account. <strong>You are liable for all activities conducted through your account</strong>, whether or not you authorized them. If you suspect that your account has been compromised (e.g., in case of unauthorized access or theft of credentials), you must notify Duvdu immediately so we can help secure your account.</li><li><strong>One Account per User:</strong> Each individual or entity is generally limited to one account on Duvdu, unless expressly permitted by us. You may not create multiple accounts for the same person, use fake identities, or register under an alias to circumvent restrictions. Similarly, you may not transfer or sell your account to another party. (Companies or organizations may have a separate account type or team arrangements as allowed by Duvdu, but such usage must comply with our rules and have proper authorization.)</li><li><strong>Account Verification:</strong> You acknowledge that Duvdu may require identity verification or other screening procedures for security and compliance purposes. For example, we may ask for government-issued identification, business documents, or verification of email and phone number. You agree to comply with such requests and authorize Duvdu to make any inquiries necessary to validate your identity and background. Failing to complete a verification process or providing false information can lead to suspension of your account.</li><li><strong>Account Use and Activity:</strong> You agree to use your account personally (if you’re an individual Freelancer or Client) or only for the business/entity you registered (if it’s a company account). You must not use another User’s account, or allow someone else to use your account, without our explicit permission. You also agree not to engage in account-sharing: each account should be used by the individual or entity that registered it.</li><li><strong>Unauthorized Access:</strong> Duvdu is not liable for any loss or damage arising from unauthorized use of your account (for example, if you fail to safeguard your login credentials). However, if we determine that Duvdu’s systems were at fault for an unauthorized access, we will take appropriate responsibility according to our policies.</li><li><strong>Refusal or Closure:</strong> We reserve the right, at our sole discretion, to refuse registration of any account, or to close an existing account, if we detect information that is fraudulent, incomplete, or otherwise in violation of these Terms. We may also reject a registration or block access in compliance with legal requirements (for example, if a user is on a sanctions list or if offering our services to them would violate the law). If your account is closed for a violation of the Terms, you may not create a new account without our prior consent.</li></ul><p>By registering on Duvdu, you agree to these eligibility conditions and acknowledge that you will uphold the obligations associated with your account.</p><p><strong>User Obligations and Acceptable Use</strong></p><p>As a condition of using Duvdu, you agree to follow these rules of acceptable use. These obligations apply to all Users (Freelancers and Clients alike) to ensure a safe, fair, and lawful environment. <strong>You agree that you will NOT:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Violate Laws or Regulations:</strong> Use the Platform for any illegal purpose or violate any laws applicable in Egypt (or in your local jurisdiction) while using Duvdu. This includes all relevant <strong>copyright laws, data protection regulations, export controls</strong>, and any other regulations. You are responsible for ensuring that your use of our services is in compliance with all applicable laws.</li><li><strong>Misrepresent or Commit Fraud:</strong> Post false, misleading, or deceptive information on your profile, project listings, proposals, or communications. You must not impersonate any person or entity, or falsely state or misrepresent your affiliation with a person or entity. Engaging in fraudulent behavior, such as promising a service and not intending to deliver, or posting a project with no intention to hire, is strictly prohibited.</li><li><strong>Infringe Intellectual Property or Other Rights:</strong> Upload, share, or otherwise make available any content that infringes or violates the intellectual property rights, privacy rights, or any other rights of any person or entity. For example, do not post images, designs, text, software, or other materials that you do not have the right to use.</li><li><strong>Post Prohibited or Harmful Content:</strong> Distribute any content through Duvdu that is unlawful, defamatory, libelous, harassing, threatening, hateful, obscene, sexually explicit, or otherwise objectionable. Content that is discriminatory (based on religion, gender, sexual orientation, race, ethnicity, etc.) or that constitutes hate speech or harassment is strictly forbidden. Additionally, do not disseminate viruses, malware, or any other harmful code that could damage the Platform or Users’ systems.</li><li><strong>Circumvent the Platform or Fees:</strong> <strong>Avoid conducting off-platform transactions for projects found on Duvdu.</strong> You agree not to circumvent or bypass Duvdu’s payment system or avoid any fees or commissions by making direct arrangements with other Users outside of Duvdu. For example, you should not share personal contact information (email, phone, etc.) or suggest alternate payment methods to a User before a project is formally agreed on the Platform. Any attempt to do so undermines the safety of the marketplace and is a violation of these Terms. (We reserve the right to charge a fee or commission equivalent to what would have been earned by Duvdu if you circumvent the Platform, and to suspend or terminate offending accounts.)</li><li><strong>Interfere with Platform Operations:</strong> Do not engage in activities that could disrupt or interfere with the functioning of the Platform. This includes attempting to hack, overload (“DDOS”), or alter the Platform’s software or underlying technology. You must not use any robot, spider, scraper, or other automated means to access the Platform for any purpose without our express written permission. Also, do not attempt to reverse engineer or decompile any of our software.</li><li><strong>Spam or Solicit Users Improperly:</strong> You may not use the Platform to send unsolicited advertising, junk mail, spam, pyramid schemes, or any other form of solicitation that is not relevant to the purpose of the Platform. Communications on Duvdu should be focused on genuine projects and work. Mass messaging for non-project purposes or to promote external products/services is not allowed.</li><li><strong>Post Inappropriate Job Listings:</strong> If you are a client, ensure that any project you post is in the appropriate category and accurately described. Do not post projects that are unrealistic, unrelated to creative/freelance work, or that violate our content guidelines (for example, jobs that solicit illegal activity or explicit content not allowed by law). Similarly, Freelancers should not post service listings or ads on the Platform outside of the designated areas or in a manner that circumvents the project posting process.</li><li><strong>Harass or Harm Others:</strong> Treat other Users with professional respect. You must not harass, stalk, or bully other Users, and you must not disclose others’ personal information obtained through the Platform (doxing). Any form of abuse, including sexual harassment or hateful conduct, will result in immediate action against your account.</li><li><strong>Use Platform for Unintended Purposes:</strong> The Platform is meant for connecting Freelancers with Clients for freelance services. You should not use it as a general communication tool to friends, a dating service, or any other use that deviates from our business purpose. Also, do not misuse any features (like feedback or rating systems) by, for instance, leaving fake reviews or artificially inflating ratings.</li><li><strong>Bypass Security Measures:</strong> You must not attempt to bypass any security features or access controls on the Platform. This includes not trying to access data that you are not authorized to access, not testing the vulnerability of the system, and not breaching or otherwise circumventing any authentication or verification measures.</li></ul><p>Violation of any of the above can lead to <strong>investigation and appropriate action</strong> by Duvdu. Such action may include warning you, removing or editing violating content, suspension of your privileges, account termination, and potential legal action depending on the severity of the violation. Duvdu also reserves the right to report any illegal activities to the appropriate law enforcement authorities. Users are expected to <strong>report any breaches</strong> of these rules they observe, by contacting Duvdu support, so we can maintain a healthy community.</p><p>By adhering to these rules, you help ensure that Duvdu remains a secure and trusted platform for everyone.</p><p><strong>Freelancer Responsibilities</strong></p><p>This section applies specifically to <strong>Freelancers</strong> (service providers on Duvdu). By offering your services as a Freelancer on the Platform, you agree to the following responsibilities and obligations:</p><ul><li><strong>Honest Representation of Skills:</strong> You will maintain an accurate profile, describing your skills, experience, qualifications, and portfolio truthfully. You will only apply for or accept projects that you are qualified for and capable of completing successfully. Misrepresenting your abilities or credentials in order to win projects is prohibited and can lead to disputes and account action.</li><li><strong>Quality of Work:</strong> You commit to delivering high-quality work that meets or exceeds the standards and requirements agreed upon with the Client. All work should be done professionally and in accordance with the specifications, timeline, and deliverables outlined in the project agreement or description. If industry standards or best practices apply to your work (for example, in graphic design, programming, etc.), you will endeavor to follow them unless otherwise directed by the Client.</li><li><strong>Timely Delivery:</strong> Respect all deadlines and timeframes agreed with the Client. It is your responsibility to manage your time and workload to fulfill your commitments. If unforeseen circumstances arise that may delay the project, you must promptly inform the Client and propose an adjusted timeline or solution. Clients are relying on you to meet deadlines, so communication about any changes is crucial.</li><li><strong>Communication:</strong> Maintain clear, polite, and timely communication with the Client throughout the Project. Respond to messages or requests from the Client as soon as feasible (generally within 1 business day, if possible). Open communication helps avoid misunderstandings — keep the Client updated on progress and ask for clarifications whenever needed. All important project communications should be kept on the Platform’s messaging system for record-keeping and safety.</li><li><strong>Original and Lawful Work:</strong> Ensure that all work and materials you deliver are your original creation, or that you have obtained all necessary rights, licenses, or permissions to use any third-party content (such as stock images, code libraries, music, etc.). The work you deliver <strong>must not infringe any copyright, trademark, trade secret, or other proprietary rights</strong> of any third party. You should also avoid using any material that the Client does not have the rights to use. If you incorporate third-party materials, inform the Client and ensure they will have the proper license to use them as part of the final deliverable.</li><li><strong>No Subcontracting without Consent:</strong> The account and reputation on Duvdu are personal to you (or your agency, if applicable). You agree to personally perform the work you commit to, unless otherwise agreed with the Client. Do not outsource or subcontract the project to another person or entity without the Client’s knowledge and approval. If you are part of a team or agency that the Client has agreed to hire, make sure this is clear from the start. Unauthorized subcontracting can be considered a breach of trust and may be grounds for dispute or account action.</li><li><strong>Use of Platform for Payments:</strong> All payments for work found through Duvdu <strong>must be processed through Duvdu’s escrow system</strong>. You must not solicit or accept payments outside the Platform for projects you get through Duvdu. By adhering to this, you protect yourself with Duvdu’s payment guarantee mechanisms and escrow protection. Requesting direct payment (e.g., bank transfer or cash) outside the Platform not only violates these Terms but also removes the protections offered by escrow.</li><li><strong>Professional Conduct:</strong> Behave professionally in all dealings. This includes delivering work that is consistent with any descriptions or samples you provided, being respectful in communications, and not engaging in any form of discrimination or inappropriate behavior toward Clients. The quality of your interactions on Duvdu can affect your reputation (through reviews/ratings), so it is in your interest to maintain professionalism.</li><li><strong>Revisions and Feedback:</strong> Be willing to make reasonable revisions or corrections if the delivered work does not meet the agreed specifications. In many creative projects, some back-and-forth is normal. However, if a client’s revision requests go beyond the original agreed scope, you have the right to discuss additional compensation or decline if it’s outside the contract – but this should be handled diplomatically and through the Platform (possibly as a scope change or new milestone).</li><li><strong>Confidentiality:</strong> If a client provides you with confidential information (for example, proprietary data, login credentials, unpublished content, etc.) for the purpose of the Project, you must keep this information confidential and use it only for the Project. Do not share the Client’s information with anyone else or use it for any purpose outside the Project. This obligation continues even after the Project is completed or your account is closed (see also Confidentiality section below).</li><li><strong>Taxes and Legal Obligations:</strong> As an independent Freelancer, you are <strong>responsible for reporting and paying any taxes applicable to your earnings</strong> through Duvdu. Duvdu does not withhold taxes from your payments unless required by law (and if so, it will be clearly communicated). It is your duty to comply with Egyptian tax laws (or any other applicable tax jurisdiction if you operate as a business). You are also responsible for obtaining any work permits or business registrations if required for freelancing. Duvdu is not responsible for any tax liabilities or government fees that you incur from your earnings on the Platform.</li></ul><p>Freelancers understand that they are <strong>independent contractors</strong> and not employees of Duvdu. You are solely responsible for your own work equipment, expenses, and methods. Duvdu does not supervise your work and does not guarantee continuous work or any income level – your success on the Platform depends on your performance and client demand. You have the freedom to determine how to complete the work (unless otherwise agreed with the Client) as long as it meets the agreed specifications. If a Freelancer fails to uphold these responsibilities, it may result in poor reviews, loss of payment (if work isn’t delivered as promised), disputes, or account suspension/termination.</p><p><strong>Client Responsibilities</strong></p><p>This section addresses the obligations of <strong>Clients</strong> (those who hire Freelancers on Duvdu). By using the Platform to find and hire Freelancers, you agree to the following:</p><p><strong>• Provide Clear Project Details (as implemented on Duvdu)</strong></p><p>On the Duvdu platform, the project workflow begins <strong>not</strong> with Clients posting project briefs, but with <strong>Service Providers (Freelancers)</strong> showcasing their own completed creative projects. This system allows Freelancers to demonstrate their capabilities through real work samples and define the type of services they offer for similar projects. Each project listing includes:</p><ul><li>A description of the <strong>original project</strong> completed by the Freelancer</li><li>The <strong>scope of work</strong> and deliverables provided</li><li><strong>Style, theme, or creative direction</strong> used</li><li><strong>Estimated price and timeline</strong> to replicate or adapt the project</li><li><strong>Booking terms</strong> for clients interested in commissioning similar work</li></ul><p>Clients then <strong>browse and search</strong> through this catalog of showcased projects to find a style or Freelancer that aligns with their needs. Once a client finds a project they like, they can <strong>book the Freelancer</strong> directly through the platform, which initiates a formal contract.</p><p>After booking:</p><ul><li>The agreed payment is <strong>deposited into Duvdu’s escrow system</strong>.</li><li>The Freelancer begins producing the <strong>new custom version of the creative material</strong> for the Client, based on the original project style and agreed-upon details.</li></ul><p>Once the new project is completed:</p><ul><li>The <strong>Freelancer submits the final work via a secure download link</strong> on the platform.</li><li>The <strong>Client has 48 hours</strong> to confirm that:<ul><li>The link works</li><li>The project meets the agreed specifications</li></ul></li></ul><p><strong>If the Client confirms</strong> within the 48-hour review window, the escrowed funds are <strong>released immediately</strong> to the Freelancer.<br><strong>If the Client takes no action</strong> within 48 hours, the system assumes the project is satisfactory, and the funds are <strong>automatically released</strong> to the Freelancer.<br><strong>If the Client rejects</strong> the project during this window, a dispute ticket is automatically generated, and the funds remain <strong>on hold</strong> in escrow <strong>until the issue is resolved</strong> by Duvdu’s support team, based on the dispute resolution process.</p><ul><li><strong>Ensure Right to Materials:</strong> If you supply the Freelancer with any content or materials (e.g., text, images, videos, data, credentials) to be used in the project, <strong>you must have the legal right to use and share those materials</strong>. You represent that providing such materials to the Freelancer will not violate any third-party’s intellectual property or privacy rights. For example, if you give a Freelancer a photo to incorporate into a design, you should either own the photo or have a license to use it. You also agree that any material you provide will not be harmful (e.g., no malware) or unlawful.</li><li><strong>Funding Escrow:</strong> Before the Freelancer begins work (especially for fixed-price projects or milestones), you agree to deposit the agreed payment amount into the Platform’s escrow system. Duvdu requires Clients to <strong>fund the project upfront into escrow</strong> to ensure the Freelancer can be paid for their work. This money will not be released to the Freelancer until you have approved the work (as described in the Escrow Payment section), but funding in advance shows commitment and assures the Freelancer that funds are available. If a project is done on an hourly or ongoing basis (if that feature exists), ensure you have a valid payment method on file and understand how you will be billed.</li><li><strong>No Start Without Escrow:</strong> You should not expect a Freelancer to begin substantial work before the project is funded in escrow. Likewise, do not make payments to the Freelancer outside the Platform. Adhering to the escrow process protects you – the funds remain safe until you’re satisfied with the work. If a Freelancer asks for direct payment off-platform, please report this to Duvdu support as it is against the Terms.</li><li><strong>Timely Communication:</strong> Once you hire a Freelancer, maintain open and timely communication. Answer any questions the Freelancer has about the project requirements. Provide feedback or direction when necessary, and do so respectfully. If you foresee delays (e.g., you need more time to gather materials or review work), inform the Freelancer. Good communication helps the project go smoothly and prevents frustration.</li><li><strong>Review and Approval:</strong> When a Freelancer submits a deliverable or milestone for your review, you agree to examine the work within a reasonable timeframe. Duvdu may specify a default review period (for example, 7 or 14 days) in its policies. It’s in everyone’s interest that you don’t unduly delay this process. If the work meets the agreed criteria, you should <strong>approve it and release the payment</strong> to the Freelancer promptly. Unreasonably withholding approval for completed work (or becoming unresponsive) is a breach of your obligations and could result in the escrow being released to the Freelancer by the Platform after the review period elapses.</li><li><strong>Feedback or Revision Requests:</strong> If the delivered work is not satisfactory or does not meet the agreed requirements, you have the right to request revisions. Provide clear and specific feedback to the Freelancer about what needs to be changed or improved. Most Freelancers will be willing to make reasonable changes to ensure you are happy, as long as those changes remain within the original scope of the project. If your feedback actually introduces new requirements that were not originally agreed, be aware the Freelancer might request an additional fee or milestone for the extra work. Try to be fair and work collaboratively to resolve any issues.</li><li><strong>Payment Release:</strong> When you are satisfied with the work (or a milestone), you must take action to release the funds from escrow to the Freelancer. On Duvdu, this is usually done by clicking a completion or approval button. Releasing payment signifies that the project (or that phase of it) is done to your satisfaction. Once released, the funds will go to the Freelancer minus any Platform fees, and you typically cannot arbitrarily reverse that decision (except through a formal dispute if something was fundamentally wrong).</li><li><strong>No Unauthorized Use of Work:</strong> Until you have paid for the work and released the funds, <strong>you do not have ownership or full rights to use the delivered work</strong> (see Intellectual Property section below). You should not use or publish any part of the Freelancer’s work beyond what is necessary for review purposes until you have fulfilled your payment obligations. If you decide not to go through with a project and get a refund, you are not entitled to use any part of the draft or partial work the Freelancer delivered. Conversely, once you pay for the work, the rights will be transferred to you as agreed – at that point, the work is yours to use as per the terms of the project.</li><li><strong>Respect and Professionalism:</strong> Treat Freelancers with respect and professionalism. Provide any resources or information the Freelancer reasonably needs to complete the project. Be mindful that Freelancers are independent professionals, not your employees – while you can expect a certain level of service and quality, you should not subject Freelancers to unfair or abusive treatment. Maintain civility even if there are disagreements. Duvdu does not tolerate harassment or discrimination against any user.</li><li><strong>Avoid Extraneous Demands:</strong> Do not demand services from the Freelancer that were not agreed upon, without offering to adjust compensation. For instance, if after seeing a design you decide to add a bunch of new features or an extra logo variation that wasn’t in the original brief, acknowledge that this changes the scope. Either create a new milestone, adjust the budget, or negotiate fairly. Do not misuse the review process to get significantly more work than initially contracted by threatening negative reviews or non-payment.</li><li><strong>Follow Dispute Process:</strong> If a serious issue arises that you cannot resolve directly with the Freelancer (for example, you believe the work is completely off the mark or the Freelancer has been unresponsive after taking payment), you agree to use Duvdu’s dispute resolution mechanism as described in these Terms. Initiate a dispute on the Platform rather than outside methods like initiating credit card chargebacks or instapay transactions, as the latter can complicate and violate the Terms. The internal dispute process is designed to handle such situations fairly (see Dispute Resolution below).</li><li><strong>Payment Methods and Charges:</strong> Ensure that your payment method on file (credit card, bank account, etc.) is valid and has sufficient funds when making payments. You authorize Duvdu to charge your payment method for amounts you fund into escrow, any Duvdu fees, and any additional charges you incur (e.g., if you purchase a premium service or if a dispute resolution fee is applicable, etc., as per our policies). You are responsible for any fees or charges assessed by your bank or payment provider (like foreign transaction fees if applicable). If a payment fails or is reversed (e.g., a chargeback), you agree to cooperate with Duvdu to resolve the issue and pay for services received.</li><li><strong>Legal Compliance:</strong> You are responsible for complying with any laws that might apply to you as a client. For example, in Egypt, if you are engaging a Freelancer as a business, ensure you abide by any labor or tax laws (though typically hiring an independent contractor through a marketplace does not create an employment relationship). If any taxes (such as VAT on digital services, or withholding taxes) apply to your payments, and if Duvdu is required by law to collect them, you agree to pay those as well. Duvdu will provide you with receipts or invoices as needed to comply with Egyptian tax regulations.</li></ul><p>By fulfilling these responsibilities, Clients help maintain a positive working environment on Duvdu and increase the likelihood of successful project outcomes. Failure to meet these obligations could result in delayed projects, disputes, lower reputation (through reviews), or even account restrictions. Duvdu’s goal is to ensure that both Clients and Freelancers have a smooth experience, and that requires cooperation and fairness from both sides.</p><p><strong>Escrow Payment System and Commission Structure</strong></p><p><strong>Escrow Funding and Release</strong></p><p>Duvdu operates a secure <strong>escrow-based payment system</strong> to ensure trust and transparency between Clients and Freelancers. Before any work begins, the Client must deposit the agreed-upon funds into Duvdu's escrow account. These funds remain securely held until the Freelancer delivers the work and the Client approves it.</p><p>If no approval or dispute is raised within <strong>48 hours</strong> after the Freelancer submits the work, Duvdu may <strong>automatically release</strong> the escrowed funds to the Freelancer. If a dispute is initiated within this window, the funds will remain in escrow until the matter is resolved through Duvdu’s dispute resolution process.</p><p>In disputes:</p><ul><li>Payments are <strong>put on hold immediately</strong>.</li><li>Resolution typically takes <strong>7–14 business days</strong>.</li><li>Duvdu may issue a <strong>partial or full refund</strong> depending on the outcome.</li><li>Freelancers agree that <strong>no payout is made</strong> if the Client’s dispute is found valid.</li></ul><p><strong>Milestone Payments</strong></p><p>Projects may be divided into <strong>milestones</strong>, each with a separate budget. Clients are required to fund each milestone in advance, and payments are released upon milestone approval. Milestones help manage risk and ensure continuous delivery and compensation in longer projects. Disputes at any milestone are isolated and do not affect funds allocated for other milestones.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Commission and Fees</strong></p><p>Duvdu follows a <strong>client-inclusive, freelancer-friendly fee model</strong>. Here’s how it works:</p><p><strong>1. No Commission Deducted from Freelancers</strong></p><p>Freelancers receive the <strong>full agreed-upon project price</strong>. Duvdu does <strong>not deduct fees from Freelancer payouts</strong>.</p><p><strong>2. Client Charges (Included in Their Total Payment)</strong></p><p>The total amount a Client pays includes:</p><ul><li><strong>Value Added Tax (VAT):</strong> 14%</li><li><strong>Transaction Fee:</strong> 3% (for processing and bank costs)</li><li><strong>Conflict Handling Fee:</strong> 3% (to support dispute resolution and platform maintenance)</li></ul><p>These fees are <strong>added on top of the project cost</strong> and do not affect the Freelancer's earnings.</p><p><strong>3. Freelancer Access Fee (After First 5 Projects)</strong></p><ul><li>Freelancers complete their <strong>first 5 projects with zero platform fees</strong>.</li><li>After that, a <strong>10% Access Fee</strong> is charged based on the total earnings from those 5 projects.</li><li>This Access Fee unlocks the <strong>next batch of 5 new client bookings</strong>.</li><li>Until the fee is paid, the Freelancer's profile remains visible but <strong>cannot accept new bookings</strong>.</li></ul><p>This <strong>“pay-after-you-earn” model</strong> is designed to minimize upfront risk and support fair earning.</p><p><strong>Payment Processing</strong></p><ul><li>Clients pay via <strong>credit/debit cards</strong>.</li><li>Freelancers withdraw via <strong>bank transfer or InstaPay</strong>.</li><li>All transactions are conducted in <strong>Egyptian Pounds (EGP)</strong>.</li></ul><p><strong>Taxes</strong></p><ul><li><strong>14% VAT</strong> is added to platform fees where applicable.</li><li>Refunds exclude VAT and fees unless otherwise decided.</li><li>Freelancers are responsible for declaring their income as per Egyptian tax laws.</li></ul><p><strong>Currency and Interest</strong></p><ul><li>All transactions are in <strong>EGP</strong>. If currency conversion occurs, the <strong>payment processor’s rates and fees apply</strong>.</li><li>Funds held in escrow <strong>do not accrue interest</strong> for users.</li></ul><p><strong>Anti-Circumvention</strong></p><p>To maintain platform integrity:</p><ul><li><strong>Off-platform payments are prohibited</strong>.</li><li>Attempts to bypass platform fees will result in <strong>account suspension or termination</strong>.</li><li>Duvdu reserves the right to <strong>recover avoided fees</strong> and enforce penalties for violations.</li></ul><p><strong>Project Delivery and Approval Process</strong></p><p>Duvdu outlines a clear process for how projects move from initiation to completion. This helps manage expectations on both sides and ensures that deliverables and payments are handled orderly. Here’s how a typical project flow works on Duvdu, from hiring to completion:</p><p><strong>Project Agreement:</strong> Once a Client finds a Freelancer (either by the Client posting a project and choosing a Freelancer, or by directly inviting/hiring a Freelancer), both parties should have a mutual understanding of the scope of work, deliverables, deadlines, and payment terms (including any milestones). It’s recommended to summarize this in writing on the Platform – for example, via the project description or messages. This written understanding will serve as the basis for judging whether the project was completed correctly.</p><p><strong>Work Begins:</strong> The Freelancer should not start significant work until the Client has funded the agreed payment into escrow (for fixed price projects or the first milestone). Once funded, the Freelancer proceeds with the project tasks as agreed. The Freelancer should manage their time to meet the deadline. If it’s an hourly project (if Duvdu supports hourly contracts in the future), the Freelancer would log hours and the Client would be billed accordingly under whatever hourly billing system exists – but for now, let’s assume fixed price since we mention escrow.</p><p><strong>Ongoing Communication:</strong> Throughout the project, the Freelancer and Client should keep communication lines open using Duvdu’s messaging system or any other agreed channel. The Freelancer might provide updates, previews, or ask clarifying questions. The Client should respond to queries and provide feedback if needed as the work progresses. Both parties should document any significant changes or agreements (for example, if the Client agrees to extend a deadline or the Freelancer agrees to include an extra small task at no charge, it’s good to note that in writing on the Platform).</p><p><strong>Delivery of Work:</strong> When the Freelancer has completed the work (or a milestone), they will deliver it to the Client. Delivery might involve uploading files via the Duvdu platform (if the platform provides a file upload/delivery mechanism), providing a download link, or even delivering in person if the nature of the project requires it (like a physical artwork or an in-person event – though for in-person, “delivery” might simply mean the service was performed). The Freelancer should explicitly indicate, “I have submitted the work for your review” or use a submission feature if available. They should ensure the Client has everything needed to evaluate the work, such as source files, preview images, or access to a demo.</p><p><strong>Client Review Period:</strong> After the Freelancer submits the work, the <strong>Client is responsible for reviewing the deliverables in a timely manner</strong>. On Duvdu, there may be a predefined time window for review (48 hours), if the Client does nothing in that time, the payment might be automatically released). Duvdu’s specific automatic release time will be communicated in the project or milestone terms. It’s important that the Client does not use this period to unnecessarily delay payment or to seek free extra work – it should be used genuinely to verify that the work meets the agreed criteria. The Client should check that all deliverables are present, they function as expected ,and match the project description or requirements.</p><p><strong>Approval and Payment Release:</strong> If the Client is satisfied that the Freelancer has completed the work according to the agreement, the Client will provide approval. This usually involves clicking a button like “Approve” or “Complete” on the Platform, which in turn triggers the release of the escrowed funds to the Freelancer. <strong>Once approved, the escrow funds are released to the Freelancer, and the transaction is considered complete</strong> (from a payment standpoint). At that point, the Freelancer will receive the payment accordingly. Approval also generally indicates that the Client is happy with the work and doesn’t intend to dispute it later.</p><p><strong>Requesting Revisions:</strong> If the Client finds that the work is not entirely what was agreed, they should promptly request revisions or point out the deficiencies. Ideally, the Client will consolidate their feedback into a clear list of issues so the Freelancer can address them efficiently. For example: “The logo you delivered is good, but I need the tagline text to be added, and one version on a transparent background.” Revisions should be within the scope of the original project agreement. The Freelancer is expected to make reasonable edits or fixes to achieve the promised outcome. Most projects allow for at least one round of revision – sometimes the number of revisions is specified upfront. The Client cannot demand unlimited changes if it wasn’t agreed; similarly, the Freelancer should be accommodating up to a reasonable point to ensure client satisfaction. It’s in both parties’ interest to collaborate and fix minor issues without escalation.</p><p><strong>Scope Creep and Changes:</strong> If during review the Client asks for changes that substantially change or increase the scope of the project (often called “scope creep”), the Freelancer should point this out and is within their rights to ask for additional compensation or a new milestone. The Client should not misuse the escrow hold to force a Freelancer to do extra work beyond what was agreed. The proper approach is to either agree on a <strong>mutually accepted modification</strong> (e.g., “I’ll do this extra feature if you increase the payment by X EGP”) and then perhaps Duvdu support can adjust the escrow amount or a new milestone is added; or to finish the current scope, release payment, and then start a new project or milestone for the new tasks. Clear communication is key: both sides should understand what is included in the price.</p><p><strong>Automatic Release (if applicable):</strong> Duvdu may have a feature where if the Client does not take action to approve or request changes within a certain period after the Freelancer’s submission, the Platform will automatically mark the project as completed and release the escrow to the Freelancer. This protects Freelancers from being indefinitely delayed by an unresponsive client. For example, if the period is 48 hours and the Client neither approves nor disputes within 48 hours of the Freelancer’s request for approval, the funds may be automatically released. Clients should be aware of this – ignoring a submission can result in losing the ability to dispute it later. If an automatic release occurs and the Client later raises an issue, it will be treated as a dispute but the funds might already be with the Freelancer, making resolution more complicated. Therefore, Clients are encouraged to actively respond. (If the Client needs more time to review, they can communicate that to the Freelancer and possibly agree to extend the review period by mutual consent, and if needed ask Duvdu support for help.)</p><p><strong>Completion and Feedback:</strong> After payment is released and the project is closed, typically the platform will allow (or prompt) both parties to leave feedback or ratings for each other. This can include a star rating and a written review. Feedback is important for the community as it helps build trust and reputation. Clients should leave fair and honest feedback reflecting the Freelancer’s work quality and professionalism. Freelancers can also rate the Client (if the platform supports that) for their communication and cooperation. Remember that reviews are generally public, and once submitted, they might not be editable (unless Duvdu’s policies allow modifications or disputes of feedback under certain circumstances like clear abuse). Duvdu might have guidelines for feedback – for example, prohibiting profanity or personal attacks. We reserve the right to remove or ask for edits to feedback that violates our content guidelines or these Terms.</p><p><strong>Handover of Materials:</strong> Once a project is completed and paid, the Freelancer should ensure the Client has received all final deliverables in the agreed format. For instance, if it’s a design project and the Client needs the source files (e.g., Photoshop or Illustrator files), those should be provided upon completion if it was part of the deal. If there were any access credentials or accounts created as part of the project (say, a website built on a server), the Freelancer should hand over control of those to the Client as appropriate after payment. Essentially, the Client should now fully “own” or have control over the work product they paid for.</p><p><strong>Client’s Use of Deliverables:</strong> After payment, the Client gains the right to use the deliverables as intended. The exact rights transferred depend on what was agreed (see Intellectual Property section). Generally, for creative work, the default is the Client receives full ownership of the final work. The Freelancer may retain the right to use general know-how or non-confidential techniques learned, but not to reuse or resell the exact deliverable. If the Client wants to give credit to the Freelancer publicly or the Freelancer wants to use the work in their portfolio, those are side considerations they can discuss (some Clients allow being featured, others don’t, it can be agreed between them).</p><p><strong>Cancellation of a Project:</strong> If at some point during the project the Client decides to cancel (or the Freelancer feels the project cannot continue, e.g., due to the Client’s lack of communication or other issues), they should communicate that clearly. A project can be cancelled by mutual agreement. If both parties agree to cancel before completion, the default is that the Client gets the escrow money back, <strong>minus any portion for work already delivered or any cancellation fee if specified</strong>. For instance, if the Freelancer has done substantial work and delivered some value before cancellation, the parties might agree that the Freelancer should be paid a fair amount for the partial work and the rest refunded. On Duvdu, initiating a cancellation might involve the Client requesting a refund from escrow and the Freelancer approving it (or vice versa). If they cannot agree on terms of cancellation (e.g., Client wants a full refund but Freelancer believes they deserve partial payment for work done), that becomes a <strong>dispute</strong> to be resolved by Duvdu (see Dispute Resolution section). We encourage trying to reach a fair compromise before escalating to a formal dispute.</p><p><strong>On-Site Services:</strong> While Duvdu is a digital platform focusing on creative services, it’s possible that some projects might involve real-world interaction (for example, a photographer hired for an event, or a graphic designer meeting the client in person to discuss ideas). If a project involves any <strong>in-person meetings or on-site work</strong>, both parties acknowledge that Duvdu is <strong>not responsible</strong> for what happens in person. Users should take appropriate precautions to ensure their own safety when meeting or working offline (meet in public places if meeting for the first time, etc.). Duvdu does not conduct background checks or in-person verifications beyond identity verification online, so be mindful when sharing personal addresses or inviting someone to a location. Any on-site work is solely at the risk and responsibility of the Client and Freelancer. Duvdu’s insurance (if any) does not cover on-the-job injuries or property damage; those arrangements would be between Client and Freelancer. For example, if a Freelancer goes to a film shoot at the Client’s property and accidentally breaks something, that would be outside of Duvdu’s purview – the two parties would have to resolve it between themselves (or through legal channels if necessary).</p><p><strong>Record-Keeping:</strong> It’s a good practice for both Clients and Freelancers to keep records of their communications and work submissions on the Platform. In case of any future misunderstandings or disputes, these records will be crucial. Duvdu’s system retains chat logs and files for a certain period, but we do not guarantee indefinite storage. If something is important, you might want to keep your own backup (for example, the final deliverables). However, sensitive information should be handled according to our confidentiality rules – don’t misuse any info you glean from the other party.</p><p>By following this process, Projects on Duvdu can proceed in an orderly way: <strong>agree, work, deliver, review, pay, and conclude</strong>. Both Clients and Freelancers have duties at each stage to ensure success. When in doubt, communicate proactively and refer back to these Terms for guidance.</p><p><strong>Dispute Resolution Mechanism</strong></p><p>While Duvdu aims to provide a Platform that fosters successful collaborations, disagreements or conflicts may occasionally arise between Clients and Freelancers. This section outlines how disputes are handled on Duvdu through our internal dispute resolution mechanism. By using the Platform, you agree to follow these steps in good faith to resolve any issues. Our goal is to help Users reach a fair resolution efficiently, but note that <strong>Duvdu is not a court of law</strong>; our decisions are a neutral attempt to resolve conflicts based on the information available. The steps for dispute resolution are as follows:</p><ul><li><strong>Attempt Amicable Resolution:</strong> In the event of a problem or dissatisfaction (e.g., the Client is not happy with the quality of work, or the Freelancer has not received payment for delivered work), the first required step is for the Client and Freelancer to <strong>communicate directly with each other</strong> and try to resolve the issue amicably. Many disputes arise from misunderstandings that can be cleared up with a conversation. The Client should clearly explain what is wrong or missing, and the Freelancer should attempt to address the concern, whether through revisions, explanations, or partial refunds as appropriate. Both parties should remain respectful and open to compromise. Most issues can be resolved at this stage without any formal intervention.</li><li><strong>Initiating a Dispute:</strong> If direct communication fails to resolve the issue, either party can initiate a formal <strong>Dispute</strong> through the Platform. To initiate a dispute on Duvdu, there may be a button or form within the project workspace (for example, “Raise Dispute”) or you may need to contact customer support indicating that you want to open a dispute. You should do this <strong>only after</strong> genuine attempts to work it out have failed. When you initiate a dispute, you will typically need to provide a summary of the issue and what resolution you are seeking (e.g., “Client refuses to pay even though work delivered,” or “Freelancer did not deliver the work as promised, I want a refund”). <strong>Timing:</strong> Disputes should be initiated within a reasonable time frame. If too much time has passed since the project was completed, it may be harder to resolve. For fixed-price projects, disputes should ideally be raised while the funds are still in escrow; once funds are released, our ability to resolve may be limited (though we can still help facilitate communication). For hourly projects (if applicable), disputes should be raised soon after the billing if there’s an issue with hours or quality.</li><li><strong>Provide Evidence and Information:</strong> Once a dispute is opened, <strong>both parties will be asked to present information and evidence</strong> regarding the situation. Duvdu may provide an interface for uploading or referencing evidence. Evidence can include:<ul><li>Communication logs (messages on Duvdu) that show what was agreed and any relevant discussions.</li><li>Work deliverables or files submitted (to prove what was delivered or not delivered).</li><li>For Freelancers: proof of work done, such as work-in-progress screenshots, source files, etc., especially if the dispute is about work quality or completeness.</li><li>For Clients: specific feedback or expert opinion if claiming the work is not as per requirements (in some cases, Clients might bring in a third-party opinion, but that’s usually not necessary).</li><li>Any other agreements made (maybe a PDF contract if one was used in addition to Duvdu’s terms, though Duvdu primarily uses the project description and messages as the contract).</li><li>If the dispute is about hours in an hourly contract (if applicable), evidence might be time logs or screenshots if the platform has a work diary.<br>Both parties should <strong>be truthful and forthcoming</strong>. Providing false information or withholding key details can not only result in losing the dispute but may also lead to account sanctions. Remember that Duvdu staff are neutral; their interest is only to get to the truth and a fair outcome. You might also be asked specific questions by the dispute mediator; respond promptly to keep the process moving.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Mediation by Duvdu:</strong> Duvdu’s dispute resolution team (the <strong>Mediator</strong>) will review the case. They may reach out to both sides for clarification or additional information. The Mediator’s role is to <strong>understand the perspectives of both parties</strong> and to assess the evidence against the original agreement and these Terms. They might facilitate a discussion by relaying messages, or they might propose a solution for both to consider. For example, the Mediator might say: “It looks like the Freelancer delivered X out of Y items, how about the escrow is split 50/50?” or “Freelancer, can you provide the missing piece by tomorrow so the Client can approve?” The exact approach can vary case by case. Duvdu might also have a tiered approach: first mediation (encouraging the parties to settle) and if that fails, then an arbitration (binding decision by Duvdu). During mediation, <strong>be cooperative and open to solutions</strong>. Many times, disputes can be settled by agreeing to a middle ground (partial refund, additional work, etc.) which the Mediator can help facilitate.</li><li><strong>Dispute Decision:</strong> If the parties cannot reach a mutual agreement during mediation, Duvdu <strong>will make a determination</strong> and decide the outcome of the dispute. This is the arbitration phase of our dispute process, where Duvdu acts as an impartial arbitrator. We will base our decision on:<ul><li>The terms of the original project agreement/scope as documented on the Platform.</li><li>The evidence provided by both sides.</li><li>Whether the work delivered substantially meets the requirements or not.</li><li>Any blatant violations of our Terms (for instance, if a Freelancer clearly plagiarized work or if a Client is clearly trying to get work for free).<br>After analysis, <strong>Duvdu’s decision can include a range of outcomes</strong>, such as:</li><li><strong>Full release of funds to the Freelancer:</strong> if we find the Freelancer delivered as promised or the Client’s complaints are not supported by evidence, we will release the escrow to the Freelancer.</li><li><strong>Full refund to the Client:</strong> if we find the Freelancer did not deliver the agreed work at all or in any acceptable form, we may refund the escrow back to the Client.</li><li><strong>Split or Partial refund/payment:</strong> if the work was partially done or the dispute is about quality where some value was delivered but not to the full expectation, we might decide to split the escrow amount in a certain proportion (e.g., 70/30, or one milestone payment each if multiple milestones in dispute, etc.) between the Freelancer and Client.</li><li><strong>Other remedial instructions:</strong> for example, we might direct the Freelancer to provide remaining files in exchange for release of funds, or the Client to receive some additional support. However, typically by the time we’re making a decision, the relationship is soured, so a monetary decision is more common than ordering more work (which wouldn’t be trusted by one party).<br>Duvdu will communicate the decision to both parties, usually with a brief explanation. Our decision is based on the <strong>standard of a reasonable person</strong> reviewing the case, not any formal legal standard. By using the Platform, you agree that our determination shall be <strong>final and binding</strong> in the context of the Platform. This means we will act on our decision (release funds accordingly) and you agree not to charge back or otherwise undo that outcome through the payment provider. We emphasize that both parties should consider the risk of dispute when entering an agreement and keep records to support their case if needed.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Duvdu Not a Judicial Authority:</strong> All Users acknowledge that Duvdu’s dispute resolution team are <strong>not professional judges or arbitrators under any national arbitration act</strong>, but we strive to resolve disputes as a neutral third party. Our goal is to be fair and consider the interests of both sides. However, <strong>Duvdu does not guarantee a perfect outcome</strong> in every dispute, and by using our service, you accept that risk. Duvdu’s involvement in disputes is a service we provide to maintain trust on the Platform, but we (including our affiliates and staff) <strong>assume no liability for the decisions made</strong> during dispute resolution. You agree to release Duvdu from claims, demands, and damages arising out of disputes with other Users, as we are only facilitating a resolution between you and the other party.</li><li><strong>5Acceptance of Duvdu’s Decision:</strong> Once Duvdu renders a decision, we will implement it. For example, if a full refund to Client is decided, we will return the escrow funds to the Client’s account or original payment source; the Freelancer will not receive payment for that project and must accept that outcome. If a split is decided, we will distribute funds accordingly. Both Client and Freelancer are expected to <strong>abide by this decision</strong>. On the Platform, this means you should not continue arguing the case or harassing the other party. You may be given an opportunity to leave feedback about each other (some platforms block feedback for disputed projects, but if allowed, keep it factual and fair). Duvdu’s decision is conclusive for the purposes of the Platform’s transaction—<strong>there is no internal appeal process</strong> beyond this, except in cases of a manifest error or new evidence that was not available (Duvdu may, at its discretion, reconsider if truly warranted, but that is rare).</li><li><strong>External Legal Remedies:</strong> Using Duvdu’s dispute mechanism does <strong>not completely waive your right to seek legal remedies outside the Platform</strong>. For instance, if a Client believes a Freelancer committed fraud or vice versa, they can still, after the dispute process, pursue legal action against the other party independently. However, you <strong>agree not to involve Duvdu</strong> in such legal disputes, because Duvdu is not a party to the contract between you. You should not name Duvdu as a defendant or claim damages from Duvdu for the other party’s actions. Additionally, the funds will likely have been distributed per Duvdu’s decision; we will not undo that unless legally compelled by a valid Egyptian court order. In practice, due to the typically small amounts in freelance projects, going to court might not be cost-effective, which is why our dispute process is valuable. But that’s your choice. Keep in mind, if you do go to court, the <strong>Governing Law</strong> section of these Terms says Egyptian law applies, and likely any lawsuit would need to be in Egypt.</li><li><strong>Chargebacks and Reversals:</strong> Clients are strongly discouraged from initiating chargebacks or payment reversals with their bank/credit card for payments made on Duvdu, especially <i>after</i> a dispute is decided. A chargeback without following the dispute process is a violation of these Terms. If a Client issues a chargeback after funds have been released to a Freelancer, Duvdu will have to investigate. This can lead to the Client’s account being suspended for violating the Terms, and Duvdu may dispute the chargeback with evidence that the service was provided. Similarly, Freelancers should not dispute payout transactions with their bank if a refund was correctly issued. If a chargeback occurs, Duvdu reserves the right to temporarily freeze other funds in the user’s account to cover the amount, and to take legal steps to recover funds if the chargeback is deemed improper. The bottom line: <strong>use Duvdu’s dispute resolution, not your card’s chargeback, to resolve issues</strong> – it’s the agreement under these Terms.</li><li><strong>Bad-Faith or Abusive Disputes:</strong> The dispute process is there to help in genuine situations; it should not be abused. Filing frivolous disputes (e.g., a Client who always disputes just to try to get free work, or a Freelancer who disputes to get paid for work clearly not done) will not be tolerated. Duvdu monitors dispute patterns, and if we detect abuse, the offending party’s account may face consequences such as loss of dispute privileges, additional fees, or termination. We strive to be fair, and we expect Users to do the same when invoking this process.</li></ul><p>Throughout the dispute resolution process, <strong>Duvdu remains neutral</strong>. We do not side with Clients or Freelancers inherently; each dispute is evaluated on its own merits. We also treat the information of the dispute confidentially; we won’t publish details of disputes (though parties might share their own experience, we advise to keep specifics private). Duvdu’s dispute team’s communications with you are also generally confidential and for the purpose of resolving the issue.</p><p>Remember: the best way to handle disputes is to avoid them by <strong>clear agreements and good communication upfront</strong>. These Terms provide a framework, but each project’s clarity is up to what you agree in writing and deliver in reality. Use the dispute mechanism as a last resort, and if you do, engage with it earnestly and respectfully for a quicker resolution.</p><p><strong>Intellectual Property Rights and Ownership of Work</strong></p><p>Intellectual property (<strong>IP</strong>) is a critical aspect of creative freelancing. This section explains how IP rights are handled for content and work created or exchanged on Duvdu, as well as each party’s rights and responsibilities concerning IP:</p><p><strong>Ownership of Deliverables (Client-Freelancer):</strong> By default, when a Freelancer creates work product for a Client as part of a project on Duvdu and is paid for that work, the <strong>intellectual property rights in the work product are transferred to the Client upon full payment</strong>. In other words, once the Freelancer has delivered the work and the Client has released the agreed payment, the Client becomes the owner of the deliverables and any IP rights (such as copyright) associated with them, unless the project agreement explicitly states otherwise. This is a common practice in work-for-hire arrangements – the buyer owns the result once it’s paid for. For example, if a Freelancer designs a logo for a Client and the Client pays for it, the Client will own that logo design outright and can use it for their business, trademark it, etc., as they see fit.</p><p><strong>Freelancer’s Warranty of Originality:</strong> The Freelancer <strong>warrants (promises) that the work they deliver is original and does not knowingly infringe upon any third-party’s IP rights</strong>. This means the Freelancer should not incorporate material they do not have the right to use. If a Freelancer does use any third-party content (like stock music, software libraries, graphics, etc.), they must ensure it’s properly licensed for the Client’s intended use and inform the Client of any applicable license terms (for instance, if a photo is used under a certain license that requires attribution, the Client should be told about that requirement). Ideally, all such specifics should be clarified in the project discussion. If the Freelancer delivers something that turns out to infringe someone else’s IP (for example, they used a pirated image or plagiarized code), the Freelancer would be liable for that breach and must indemnify the Client (see Indemnification section) and/or resolve it (for example, by obtaining a correct license or replacing the infringing part with something original).</p><p><strong>Client’s Use of Delivered Work:</strong> Until the Client releases payment for a given deliverable, the work remains the intellectual property of the Freelancer. The Client is essentially “licensing” it for review purposes during the project but does not own it yet. Therefore, <strong>Clients should not use or publish the work publicly or commercially before they have paid for it in full</strong> (unless the Freelancer explicitly agrees otherwise in writing). Once payment is made, the <strong>Client obtains rights</strong> as agreed – typically full ownership (for things like unique designs, code written for them, etc.), or possibly a license in some cases (for example, if a Freelancer is offering a pre-existing template or piece of code under certain terms). However, unless something different was specified, assume it’s a full transfer of rights to the Client. This includes rights to modify, reproduce, distribute, or publicly display the work. Freelancers should not retain any rights to use the work except as allowed (like in a portfolio, see below) and should not resell the exact same work to others.</p><p><strong>Freelancer Portfolio Rights:</strong> Freelancers often wish to showcase their work to get more business. By default, after a project is completed, a Freelancer <strong>may have the right to reference or display a portion of the work in their portfolio or personal promotional materials</strong>, <strong>unless</strong> the Client has requested confidentiality or a non-disclosure that prevents this. Many Clients are fine with Freelancers showcasing non-sensitive parts of a project (like a watermarked version of a design or a snippet of code, or simply naming the project/Client) because it helps the Freelancer grow and doesn’t harm the Client. However, if a project is confidential or the deliverables are meant to be private (common in things like unreleased marketing campaigns, proprietary software, ghostwritten content, etc.), the Client should inform the Freelancer that they <i>cannot</i> use it in a portfolio. If the Client doesn’t specify and there’s no NDA, it’s generally acceptable for the Freelancer to include the work in a portfolio as an example of their experience. That said, the Freelancer should still respect any confidential details (e.g., not expose the Client’s confidential strategy or data within the portfolio piece).</p><p><strong>Moral Rights (if applicable):</strong> In some jurisdictions, creators have “moral rights” like the right to be attributed (credit for the work) or the right to object to derogatory modifications of their work. If such rights exist under applicable law, the Freelancer typically agrees to waive those rights to the extent allowed, or not to enforce them, so that the Client can use the work freely (especially if the Client will modify it later). However, Egypt doesn’t allow complete waiver of moral rights under its copyright law (authors have perpetual moral rights). For practical purposes though, since this is a work-for-hire scenario, the Freelancer consents that the Client may use or even modify the work without attributing the Freelancer if they so choose. If the Client does give credit (like in a published artwork, “Design by X”), that’s a courtesy unless contractually required.</p><p><strong>Client Materials:</strong> Conversely, if a Client provides materials to the Freelancer to incorporate or as reference (text, images, logos, etc.), the Client either retains ownership of those materials or has licensed them from a third party. The Client giving those materials to the Freelancer is not a transfer of ownership – it’s for the purpose of the project. The Freelancer can only use those Client-provided materials for the Client’s project and must not use them elsewhere without permission. For example, if a Client gives a Freelancer a proprietary font file or a dataset to use in a design, the Freelancer should not copy that font or data for other projects or personal use beyond what is needed for the Client’s work.</p><p><strong>User Content on the Platform:</strong> Apart from the deliverables of a project, Users also post other content on Duvdu – profiles, reviews, messages, etc. Duvdu does not claim ownership of the content that Users post. <strong>However, by posting content on the Platform, you grant Duvdu a license to use that content as needed to operate and market the Platform</strong>. For example, if you upload a profile picture or a portfolio example, you give us the right to display it on our site, maybe use it in promotional materials for Duvdu (like showing top freelancers). This license is <strong>non-exclusive, worldwide, royalty-free, and sub-licensable</strong> (so we can allow our affiliates or contractors to deliver our services). It’s mainly so we don’t get in trouble for showing what you provided to us. We won’t, for instance, sell your content to others or claim it’s ours – it’s just to run our site (this is standard in user-generated content terms). You can remove certain content (like updating your profile) and that will end our license for new use, but note if it was already used (like in a screenshot for an ad), that may persist.</p><p><strong>Duvdu’s Intellectual Property:</strong> The Platform itself (our software, design, logo, brand name, etc.) is protected by IP laws. Using Duvdu does not give you any ownership of our intellectual property. You agree not to use the name “Duvdu” or our logos without permission, except as needed to factually describe your use of our service. (For example, a freelancer can say “I use Duvdu to find clients” – that’s fine, but you can’t brand yourself as being affiliated or endorsed by Duvdu without a specific agreement.)</p><p><strong>Reporting IP Infringement:</strong> Duvdu respects intellectual property rights. If you believe a User on Duvdu has infringed your IP (or someone else’s) – for instance, a Freelancer’s profile contains images from another artist used without permission – you can notify us via our <strong>Copyright/IP Policy</strong> (typically by sending a notice to our designated email). We will investigate such claims and may remove or disable content that is infringing. Repeated infringers will be banned. Users should also be careful not to upload anything they don’t have rights to. If Duvdu receives a credible takedown notice (like a DMCA notice in the US context, or similar under Egyptian law) about content you posted, we may remove it and notify you.</p><p><strong>Confidential Projects and NDAs:</strong> Sometimes a Client may require a <strong>Non-Disclosure Agreement (NDA)</strong> for a project, especially if sensitive information is involved. Duvdu may offer a standard NDA that can be digitally signed by both parties, or parties can have their own NDA. If an NDA is in place, the Freelancer must abide by its stricter terms regarding confidentiality and possibly IP (some NDAs/contract will explicitly say “all work produced under this contract is work-made-for-hire and belongs to the Client” which aligns with what we already said). If there’s any conflict between a custom NDA and these Terms regarding IP, usually the NDA (as a more specific agreement between those parties) would take precedence for that project’s specifics, but these Terms cover everything else. Keep in mind, Duvdu itself is not bound by your NDA between Client and Freelancer (though we have our own privacy obligations), because Duvdu is not a party to that contract.</p><p>In summary, <strong>Clients get what they pay for</strong> – they own the completed work once payment is done, and <strong>Freelancers retain rights to their own pre-existing materials</strong> but give the Client the needed rights in the new work. Both should respect each other’s intellectual property outside the scope of the project: e.g., Clients shouldn’t reuse a Freelancer’s proposal or concept they didn’t pay for, and Freelancers shouldn’t reuse a Client’s task or data for others. When in doubt, discuss and clarify any specific IP concerns before the project starts.</p><p><strong>Confidentiality and Privacy</strong></p><p>In the course of using Duvdu, Users may share sensitive or proprietary information with each other. Maintaining confidentiality is key to trust on the platform, especially for creative projects that might involve unreleased content or personal data. This section outlines how Users should handle confidential information and personal data:</p><p><strong>Confidential Information Definition:</strong> “Confidential Information” refers to any non-public information that a party discloses to the other in relation to a project that is either marked as confidential or would reasonably be understood to be confidential given the nature of the information and the context of disclosure. This can include (but isn’t limited to) business plans, marketing strategies, unpublished designs, source code, client lists, financial information, trade secrets, inventions, and any other data that is not generally known publicly. It also includes any <strong>personal data</strong> shared, like a Client’s customer data or a Freelancer’s personal contact info provided for work purposes (outside what’s public on their profile).</p><p><strong>Obligation to Keep Confidence:</strong> Both Clients and Freelancers <strong>agree to keep confidential information private and not disclose it to anyone outside the project</strong> without the prior written consent of the party that provided it. If you receive confidential data, you should use it only for the purposes of completing the project or fulfilling your obligations under this Agreement. For example, if a Client shares a new product concept with a Freelancer so they can create a marketing video, the Freelancer must not reveal that product concept to others or use it for any purpose other than making the video for the Client.</p><p><strong>Exceptions:</strong> Generally, the confidentiality obligation does <strong>not</strong> apply to information that:</p><ul><li>Is already publicly available (through no breach by the receiving party – e.g., the info was in the news or on a website publicly).</li><li>Was already in the receiving party’s possession before disclosure, as long as they didn’t get it from the disclosing party (and not under another confidentiality obligation).</li><li>Was independently developed by the receiving party without reference to the confidential info (you’d need proof of independent development).</li><li>Is obtained from a third party who had the right to share it (i.e., they weren’t under confidentiality either).</li><li>Is required to be disclosed by law or legal process (see next point).</li></ul><p><strong>Legal Disclosure:</strong> If you are required by law, court order, or government authority to disclose confidential information provided by the other party, you may do so, <strong>but</strong> you should (to the extent legally allowed) notify the other party beforehand so they have a chance to contest the disclosure or seek a protective order. For instance, if a court subpoena compels a Freelancer to produce work they did for a Client, the Freelancer should inform the Client so they can attempt to limit the scope or protect certain sensitive parts.</p><p><strong>Return or Destruction:</strong> Upon completion of a project or at any time upon the disclosing party’s request, the receiving party should return or destroy any confidential materials of the other party in their possession. For example, if a Client provided raw videos to a video editor (Freelancer), after the project the Client might ask them to delete all footage from their drives. The Freelancer should comply (except for one backup if needed for minor revisions until the project is clearly done, but once confirmed, remove it). The exception may be any copies that need to be kept for legal compliance or internal records (like an archive backup), but those remain confidential indefinitely.</p><p><strong>Duration:</strong> How long does the confidentiality obligation last? Typically, <strong>confidentiality obligations continue even after the project is finished and after account termination</strong>. A common duration is at least 2 years, or sometimes indefinite until the information becomes public from another source. Given creative projects often have long product cycles, we will say it lasts indefinitely until the info is public by other means. Users should assume they must keep the secret as long as it’s a secret.</p><p><strong>Privacy and Personal Data:</strong> Use of the Duvdu Platform is also subject to our <strong>Privacy Policy</strong> (which is a separate document detailing how we collect, use, and protect personal data of Users). Both Clients and Freelancers should respect each other’s personal data. You should not use personal contact information obtained through Duvdu for anything outside project communication. For example, a Freelancer might learn a Client’s email or phone – they should not add it to marketing lists or share it. Similarly, a Client might get a Freelancer’s CV or ID for verification on a project (like if needed for a permit); they should keep that safe and not share it around.</p><p><strong>Duvdu’s Role:</strong> Duvdu’s staff will also have access to communications and files exchanged on the Platform (as needed for support or monitoring). Duvdu will treat user communications and files as confidential as per our Privacy Policy, but note that we may need to review them during disputes or platform moderation. We typically won’t share them with third parties except as needed for providing the service (e.g., storing on our cloud servers) or if required by law.</p><p><strong>Non-Use:</strong> Even if something isn’t strictly a “secret,” users should not misuse information obtained through the Platform. For example, if a Freelancer learns through working with a Client about their internal business processes or upcoming projects, the Freelancer shouldn’t use that knowledge to compete with the Client or for personal gain. Same goes for Clients: if a Client learns a Freelancer’s proprietary technique or tool usage, the Client shouldn’t steal that method and share it with another provider without permission, unless it’s something commonly known.</p><p><strong>Publicity:</strong> Unless agreed otherwise, Freelancers and Clients can’t use each other’s names, logos, or trademarks in an advertising or publicity manner without consent. For instance, a Freelancer shouldn’t put the Client’s logo on their website as a client reference without permission (though usually many clients are fine with being listed, it’s polite to ask). Conversely, a Client shouldn’t say “our partner Duvdu Freelancer Name did this for us” in a press release without checking with the Freelancer. One exception: a Client can publicly review a Freelancer on Duvdu and vice versa – that’s allowed because it’s part of the Platform’s social proof, and the user agrees to that by using the platform. Those reviews themselves must still abide by confidentiality (don’t mention the secret project details in a public review).</p><p><strong>Security:</strong> Both parties should apply reasonable security measures to protect the other’s confidential information. For example, if a Client shares access to a staging server or a social media account for the project, the Freelancer should keep those credentials safe, not reuse them for other purposes, and not share with anyone else. If a Freelancer downloaded some client files, they should ensure their device is secure (use antivirus, don’t leave laptop unattended, etc.). In case of any suspected breach (like you think someone hacked into something or you accidentally emailed a file to the wrong address), inform the other party immediately and cooperate to mitigate any damage.</p><p>In summary, <strong>discretion and trust</strong> are vital. Many creative works are sensitive until officially released, and business data is often confidential. By agreeing to these Terms, <strong>both Clients and Freelancers commit to respecting each other’s confidential and personal information</strong>, just as they would want their own to be respected.</p><p><strong>Disclaimer of Warranties</strong></p><p><strong>Use at Your Own Risk:</strong> Your use of the Duvdu Platform and any services or work obtained through the Platform is <strong>at your own risk</strong>. Duvdu provides its services on an “<strong>as is</strong>” and “<strong>as available</strong>” basis. This means that we do not make any promises or guarantees about the Platform’s availability, reliability, or suitability for your needs beyond what is explicitly stated in these Terms.</p><p><strong>No Warranty of Results:</strong> <strong>Duvdu makes no warranties or representations</strong> about the success of any project, the quality of any Freelancers or Clients, or the ability of either party to fulfill their obligations. While we may provide profiles, ratings, portfolios, and other data to help Users make decisions, we <strong>do not guarantee</strong> that any Freelancer’s work will meet your expectations or that any project will be completed to your satisfaction. Similarly, we cannot guarantee that Clients will always be honest or pay promptly, though our escrow system mitigates payment risks.</p><p><strong>Platform Functionality:</strong> We do not warrant that the Platform will be <strong>uninterrupted, error-free, or completely secure</strong>. We strive to maintain a high uptime and quickly fix issues, but outages or bugs may occur. We do not warrant that any browser or device will be fully compatible with our site or app. For example, there might be times when maintenance causes downtime, or an unforeseen technical problem occurs. We also can’t guarantee the Platform will be free from viruses, malware, or other harmful components, though we take security seriously. It’s advisable that you have your own protections (like updated antivirus software).</p><p><strong>No Implied Warranties:</strong> To the fullest extent permitted by law, <strong>Duvdu disclaims all implied warranties</strong>. This includes implied warranties of <strong>merchantability</strong> (that the service would meet a basic level of quality or functionality), <strong>fitness for a particular purpose</strong> (that it would be suitable for your specific needs), <strong>non-infringement</strong> (that using the platform won’t infringe third-party rights), and any others that might be implied by law. Essentially, we’re not guaranteeing that the Platform is perfect or will do exactly what you want it to do.</p><p><strong>User Content and Outside Information:</strong> Content posted by Users (like profiles, job descriptions, reviews, etc.) is not pre-approved by Duvdu. We do not warranty the <strong>accuracy or truthfulness</strong> of any User-generated content. For example, if a Freelancer claims to be an expert in 3D animation or if a Client describes a project as a great opportunity, we aren’t verifying those statements in most cases. You should use your judgment .We do reserves the right to remove or edit content that violates our policies, but in general, <strong>proceed with due diligence</strong> when engaging with other Users.</p><p><strong>No Warranty as to Identity Verification:</strong> While we may offer verification tools (e.g., checking IDs or linking social profiles), <strong>Duvdu does not guarantee each person’s identity</strong>. You should understand that user verification on the internet isn’t foolproof. We provide a platform for transactions, but the actual contract of service is between Client and Freelancer, and each must satisfy themselves about the other’s identity and trustworthiness. We encourage you to use video calls or other methods if identity is a concern, but even then, our warranty is not covering fraudulent impersonations beyond reasonable measures.</p><p><strong>No Warranty on Deliverables:</strong> Any work product delivered by Freelancers is the responsibility of those Freelancers. Duvdu doesn’t control, oversee, or guarantee the <strong>quality, safety, legality, or appropriateness</strong> of the Freelancer’s work. We do not provide any warranty that a delivered piece of software will be bug-free, or a design will be original, or that a given strategy will yield results. Those are outside our control. Our only role is to facilitate the connection, payment, and if needed, dispute resolution. <strong>Clients must review and accept work at their own discretion</strong>; once you approve a deliverable and release payment, that is your decision and responsibility.</p><p><strong>Third-Party Services:</strong> If the Platform integrates or links to any third-party services (for example, payment gateways, cloud storage for file transfer, communication tools, etc.), Duvdu makes no warranty regarding those services either. They are provided for convenience, but any malfunction or breach on their side is not warranted by us (though we will try to help Users navigate issues). For instance, if a payment processor has downtime, we can’t warrant against that (though we’d switch to another or resolve after).</p><p><strong>Beta Features:</strong> Occasionally, Duvdu might offer new features in beta (testing) mode. Any such features will be labeled beta and are provided “as is” with no warranty. They might change, break, or be removed at any time.</p><p><strong>Summation:</strong> To be clear, <strong>Duvdu does not guarantee any specific outcome from the use of the Platform</strong>. We do not guarantee continuous availability, we do not guarantee any financial benefit, and we do not provide warranties like a traditional product or service might (because much depends on the independent Users). Our role is to make a functional marketplace, and while we put in effort to make it reliable and secure, <strong>there are no guarantees</strong>. By accepting these Terms, you agree that you understand this and that you’ll not hold Duvdu responsible for the inherent risks of using an online freelance platform.</p><p><strong>Limitation of Liability</strong></p><p>To the extent permitted by law, Duvdu’s liability to Users is limited. This means that if something goes wrong, the amount and types of damages you can recover from us are restricted. Read this section carefully to understand the extent of our obligations (or lack thereof) in various scenarios.</p><p><strong>Indirect or Consequential Damages:</strong> <strong>In no event will Duvdu or its affiliates, officers, directors, employees, or agents be liable for any indirect, incidental, special, consequential, or punitive damages</strong> arising out of or related to your use of the Platform or these Terms. This includes, for example:</p><ul><li><strong>Lost profits or revenue:</strong> if you expected to earn money (as a Freelancer) or save money (as a Client) and that didn’t happen due to some issue with our Platform, we are not responsible for your lost income or business opportunities.</li><li><strong>Loss of data:</strong> if data (like messages or files) is lost or corrupted on our Platform (perhaps due to a system