n</strong>, particularly (but not only) in the following circumstances:</p><ul><li><strong>Breach of Terms:</strong> If you violate any of these Terms or any other policy (e.g., attempting to circumvent fees, engaging in harassment, posting prohibited content, etc.), we may suspend or terminate your account.</li><li><strong>Serious Misconduct:</strong> Certain actions may lead to immediate termination without warning, such as fraud, theft, repeated intellectual property infringement, running scams, or activities that could harm other users or the Platform.</li><li><strong>Legal Compliance:</strong> If required by law enforcement or regulatory authorities (e.g., if a user is found engaging in unlawful transactions or we receive a court order), we may restrict or close the account.</li><li><strong>Inactive Accounts:</strong> We may have a policy to terminate or archive accounts that have been inactive for a very long period (e.g., 1-2 years) for security and cleanup, after notice.</li><li><strong>Security Concerns:</strong> If we detect that an account may have been compromised or is being used in a suspicious manner (e.g., multiple login attempts from different countries in short time, or as part of a fraud ring), we might temporarily suspend while we investigate.</li><li><strong>Non-Payment or Fee Avoidance:</strong> For freelancers, if due commissions are not paid or for clients, if chargebacks are made improperly, etc., we may freeze or close the account.</li><li><strong>Repeated Poor Behavior:</strong> If a user accumulates multiple poor reviews or complaint reports (even if not outright term violations) we might investigate and decide that the user isn’t a good community member, leading to suspension or termination.</li></ul><p><strong>Notice:</strong> While we reserve the right to act without prior notice, in many cases we will attempt to notify you via email or Platform message of the suspension or termination and the reason (unless legally prevented or if we deem it that providing details could cause harm). For example, a warning for a first-time minor violation might be given, whereas blatant abuse might result in instant termination.</p><p><strong>Effect of Suspension:</strong> If your account is suspended:</p><ul><li>You will likely not be able to bid on new projects or initiate new transactions.</li><li>You may still be able to log in to resolve existing projects or communicate with us, but features may be limited.</li><li>If we suspend due to an ongoing investigation (e.g., fraud check), we might also freeze any funds in your account until that is resolved.</li><li>Suspension can be lifted if the issue is resolved or you appeal successfully, but there’s no guarantee.</li></ul><p><strong>Effect of Termination (Platform-Wide):</strong> If your account is terminated by us:</p><ul><li>All active projects may be <strong>cancelled</strong>. We will handle funds in escrow on a case-by-case basis. Usually, if a user is terminated for misconduct, and they are a freelancer, any funds in escrow might be refunded to the client (especially if the freelancer didn’t deliver). If a client is terminated (e.g., for fraud) and there’s escrow, we might refund it to them or hold it – depends on the context (like if a freelancer delivered work already).</li><li>You will lose access to your account entirely. Your profile will likely be removed or anonymized.</li><li>Any pending balance (earnings that were available for withdrawal) may be forfeited or delayed. If you violated terms, we may offset damages or fees against your balance. If not related to a violation, we might still allow a withdrawal (except in fraud cases where we might be compelled to return funds to victims).</li><li>You are <strong>not allowed to create a new account</strong>. If we catch evasion (same person opening a new account), those may be terminated too. We may use various signals (email, payment info, IP, etc.) to detect this.</li><li>Some provisions of this Agreement will survive even after termination – e.g., confidentiality, IP granted to clients, indemnification, limitation of liability, etc.</li></ul><p><strong>Appeals:</strong> If you think your account was wrongfully suspended or terminated, you can contact our support or appeals channel to request a review. We will consider your explanation and any evidence, and decide at our discretion whether to reinstate. We do not guarantee reinstatement. Decisions for permanent bans are usually final, particularly if we have evidence of severe violations.</p><p><strong>Account Holds and Other Measures:</strong> Apart from suspension/termination, Duvdu can also:</p><ul><li>Issue warnings or require you to complete certain actions (like verify identity or remove content) to continue using the account.</li><li>Remove or hide specific content (like a project listing or a review) that violates our policies.</li><li>Temporarily disable payouts or apply a hold on funds (for example, during a dispute or fraud investigation).</li><li>Downgrade your account privileges (like revoke a Freelancer’s status in some program, or prevent a Client from posting new jobs until an issue is resolved).</li></ul><p><strong>Effect on Ongoing Contracts:</strong> If an account is terminated mid-project, we will attempt to minimize harm:</p><ul><li>If a freelancer is terminated while working on a project, the client will likely get their escrow back (or in rare cases, a portion might be released if the freelancer substantially delivered).</li><li>If a client is terminated mid-project (say for payment fraud), the freelancer might not get paid for that project (especially if it was fraudulent funding). We know that’s tough, but we can’t pay out from a fraudulent source. We’ll try to assist the freelancer, maybe returning files or such, but they might have to cut losses.</li><li>Duvdu might step in to inform the other party of what happened in generic terms (“this user can no longer continue on the platform”) and possibly help them via dispute process or support to sort out any remaining issues.</li></ul><p><strong>Liability for Prior Transactions:</strong> Even after termination, you (or we) could still be held liable for things that occurred before termination. For example, if a client is terminated but they owe a freelancer for completed work, they are still contractually obligated to pay (the freelancer could pursue them outside the platform if needed). Or if a freelancer is terminated but delivered subpar work that caused damages, they might still face legal claims. Termination doesn’t erase responsibility for past breaches of contract or law.</p><p><strong>Survival of Terms:</strong> As mentioned, <strong>certain clauses survive</strong> termination, such as confidentiality, IP rights transfer, limitation of liability, indemnity, governing law, etc. So you can’t avoid those obligations by leaving the platform.</p><p><strong>No Refund of Fees:</strong> If you paid any membership fees or premium services (if applicable), those are typically not refunded if your account is terminated for cause. If we terminate at our convenience (not due to your wrongdoing), we might consider pro-rata refunds, but in most user-initiated or cause-based terminations, no refunds.</p><p><strong>Multiple Users / Agency Accounts:</strong> If you are part of an agency or team account and one member is terminated, we may or may not terminate the whole team account depending on involvement. If an agency is a single legal entity account and it’s terminated, all team members lose access.</p><p><strong>Contact After Termination:</strong> Once terminated, you should not use the platform. If you need to communicate with us (like to retrieve final funds or information), do so through email. Any attempt to circumvent a ban can result in legal action if extreme (like if someone keeps harassing the platform after being banned).</p><p>In essence, <strong>Duvdu has broad discretion to manage our community by removing bad actors or mitigating risks</strong>. We take that seriously to maintain a trustworthy environment. However, we are also fair; we don’t terminate lightly, especially for active users, unless necessary.</p><p><strong>Governing Law and Jurisdiction</strong></p><p>It is important to establish which country’s laws govern this Agreement and where disputes will be resolved. For Duvdu, since we operate in Egypt and serve users in Egypt, we choose <strong>Egyptian law</strong> as the governing law. This section confirms that choice and the jurisdiction of courts.</p><p><strong>Governing Law:</strong> <strong>This Agreement and your use of Duvdu will be governed by and construed in accordance with the laws of the Arab Republic of Egypt</strong> (the “Governing Law”). We explicitly exclude any application of the United Nations Convention on Contracts for the International Sale of Goods (which is irrelevant anyway since this is not a sale of goods contract, but we exclude it to avoid any confusion). Also, we do not apply any conflicts of law principles that would result in applying another jurisdiction’s laws. In practice, this means that if there is a dispute that goes to court, Egyptian substantive law will be used to interpret and enforce this contract.</p><p>Egyptian law covers the basics of contracts, and since this is a service and platform context, it will include Egyptian civil code and electronic commerce regulations (if any specifically apply). By agreeing to Egyptian law, both parties (Users and Duvdu) have a consistent legal framework. If you’re using Duvdu, you should be aware of Egyptian legal standards for things like contracting, liability, IP rights, etc., because they will apply.</p><p><strong>Jurisdiction (Forum Selection):</strong> <strong>You agree that any disputes or claims arising out of or relating to this Agreement or your use of the Platform that cannot be resolved amicably or through our internal dispute resolution will be brought exclusively in the courts of the Arab Republic of Egypt</strong>. We may specify a particular city’s courts, often it’s where the company is registered or headquartered “the competent civil courts in Cairo, Egypt”</p><p>This means if you want to sue Duvdu, you need to do it in Cairo, Egypt. If Duvdu wants to sue you (for something like fees due or injunctive relief for misuse), we would do so in Egypt (unless it’s to enforce a judgment or something in another country, but that’s separate). This clause aims to prevent multi-jurisdictional litigation and ensures that any legal dispute between us goes to an Egyptian court, which we consider our home turf and presumably where we have our legal resources.</p><p><strong>Waiver of Objection:</strong> By agreeing to these Terms, you waive any objection to the Egyptian courts exercising jurisdiction over you. This is sometimes called <strong>“consent to jurisdiction”</strong> (meaning you won’t claim it’s an inconvenient forum). So even if you are a user located in another country, you accept that coming to Egypt’s courts is the method to resolve serious disputes (if not handled by arbitration or our dispute process).</p><p><strong>Injunctive Relief Exception:</strong> We might state that nothing in this section prevents Duvdu from seeking injunctive relief in any appropriate jurisdiction. This is to handle situations like if a user infringes our IP or hacks our system, we might need to quickly go to a court in their jurisdiction or elsewhere to stop it, rather than waiting for Egyptian courts. Often Terms mention that you agree the company can apply to any court for injunctive remedies to protect its rights or enforce certain obligations (like confidentiality or IP).</p><p><strong>Legal Proceedings and Notices:</strong> If any lawsuit is filed, it’ll be under Egyptian court procedures. Typically, each party will bear its own legal fees unless the court awards fees to the winner. Our Terms could mention, that the prevailing party in a dispute shall be entitled to costs and attorneys’ fees.</p><p><strong>Final Note:</strong> If a dispute between a Client and Freelancer goes to court, since Duvdu is not a party, they might sue each other elsewhere depending on their own situation (like if they are in the same country outside Egypt maybe). But Duvdu’s involvement is minimal there. This governing law clause mainly covers disputes between Users and Duvdu or any claim relating to the platform usage.</p><p>By using Duvdu, <strong>you are effectively agreeing that Egyptian law governs your relationship with Duvdu and that you will litigate in Egypt if it comes to that</strong>.</p><p><strong>Changes to Terms</strong></p><p>Duvdu may update or modify these Terms and Conditions from time to time. As the business environment, laws, or platform features evolve, we need to ensure our Terms remain current. Here is how changes to the Terms will be handled:</p><ul><li><strong>Right to Modify:</strong> <strong>Duvdu reserves the right to modify or update this Agreement at any time</strong>. We might do this for various reasons, such as changes in our services, changes in the law, introduction of new features, or to clarify existing terms.</li><li><strong>Notice of Changes:</strong> If we make material changes to the Terms, we will <strong>notify users in an appropriate manner</strong>. This could include:<ul><li>Posting an announcement or notification on our website or within the mobile app (for example, a banner or an in-app alert).</li><li>Sending an email to the email address associated with your account, informing you of the update.</li><li>Other communication means (we might also blog about it or use social media, but the primary methods would be direct notice on platform or email).</li></ul></li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><ul><li><strong>Acceptance of Changes:</strong> <strong>Continued use of the Platform after the effective date of updated Terms constitutes your acceptance of the changes.</strong>. This