n, we still have the right to take action later or enforce that term in the future with you or other users. Any waiver of any provision of the Terms will only be effective if in writing and signed by an authorized representative of Duvdu. Similarly, a single or partial exercise of a right doesn’t prevent us from later exercising the full right.</li><li><strong>Severability:</strong> <strong>If any provision of these Terms is held to be invalid, illegal, or unenforceable by a court of competent jurisdiction, that provision will be severed (removed) from the Terms</strong>, and the remaining provisions will remain in full force and effect. In such a case, we would likely replace the invalid provision with a new one that achieves the original intent as much as legally possible. The idea is that one problematic clause doesn’t void the entire Agreement. For example, if a court said the limitation of liability is too broad to be enforceable under local law, that part might be modified by the court or treated in a way that fits the law, but the rest of the Agreement would still apply.</li><li><strong>Relationship of Parties:</strong> <strong>Duvdu is not a party to contracts between Clients and Freelancers</strong> , and nothing in this Agreement creates any partnership, joint venture, agency, employer-employee, or franchisee-franchisor relationship between Duvdu and any User. <strong>You and Duvdu are independent contractors</strong> with respect to each other. Likewise, Clients and Freelancers are independent contractors vis-à-vis each other (the Freelancer is not an employee of the Client via Duvdu’s platform, unless they separately agree otherwise off-platform, which we aren’t part of. This clause basically means: you cannot act in Duvdu’s name, and we don’t control you like an employer would. For instance, Duvdu doesn’t withhold taxes for freelancers as an employer would, and using the platform doesn’t make Duvdu your agent beyond the limited role of payment agent in 